<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="27" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1791,2034]" pageId="5" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1791,1816]" pageId="5" pageNumber="27">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Hübner, 1819" authorityName="Hübner" authorityYear="1819" box="[401,539,1792,1816]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Diacrisia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lentifasciata">
<emphasis box="[401,539,1792,1816]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="27">lentifasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except facies pale orange-yellow. Interneural patches present but faint, and the dorsal patches on the abdomen are replaced by small black dots. Unlike 
<taxonomicName authority="Hübner, 1819" authorityName="Hübner" authorityYear="1819" box="[1015,1153,1828,1852]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Diacrisia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lentifasciata">
<emphasis box="[1015,1153,1828,1852]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="27">lentifasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the valvae are swollen basally and lack dorsolateral processes. The finely pointed terminal extensions of the juxta are lightly curved and reach the base of the uncus.
</paragraph>
